Breast Cancer: Malignant or Benign? Using SHAP values to examine feature importance of physical characteristics and make predictions¶

We have a dataset on whether a breast cancer was classified as malignant or benign in addition to various features for each.

With this data, it would be nice to have a model that is able to make predictions on the diagnosis based on these physical features.

A practical application of this would be to examine the features, and identify which seem to be most correlated with malignant cancers.

This could help medical providers determine what physical characteristics to look for most, make decisions, and reinforce their professional intuition to make decisions. For patients, this may identify useful rule-of-thumb characteristics to immediately contact their healthcare provider about, such as a change in texture. For researchers, this may identify features that spending the effort to collect data for is not very fruitful.

Data: https://www.kaggle.com/datasets/nancyalaswad90/breast-cancer-dataset

Identifying Correlation¶

Plotting some example variables together

radius and perimeter, two size-related features have a correlation of 0.987

while radius and smoothness are a size feature and a texture feature and have a correlation of only 0.323

In [12]:
#Plot radius vs perimeter
plt.scatter(df.radius_mean,df.perimeter_mean)
plt.xlabel("Radius")
plt.ylabel("Perimeter")
plt.show()

As expected these two features almost form a perfect line. As a result we may consider doing some dimensionality reduction and using only one of these features.

As expected these two features do not seem to form any uniform distribution.

Exploration of the prediction for a single patient based on the features. This explanation was made for an existing patient, but can easily be used for future patients by using the model to predict for a new row of data.

The arrows on the force plot represent both the direction and magnitude of each features' contribution. Features that are below the threshold are not labelled and are less important.

As determined in the SHAP values above, symmetry and compactness are two major features that drive the prediction downward, while features related to size such as radius and perimeter greatly drive the prediction upward. This is in line with expectations.

For this individual patient, the prediction is much higher than the base value. Based on the feature values, the model predicts that this particular cancer is malignant.

Results¶

  • Trained models & compared to select the model with best performance to make future predictions with for individual patients, or to further optimize as desired

  • Used heatmap to visualize correlation between features, and set up a good starting point for feature engineering to further push better model performance

  • Ran Permutation Importance to identify the most impactful features. Likewise, some features actually turn out to be rather useless.

  • Used SHAP values and convienent visuals to easily identify the features that strongly increase or decrease the diagnosis prediction and explore their contribution

  • Extended the usage of SHAP values to individual patients and cancers, visualizing with all features at once to show how the overall prediction is obtained
